Ancient Egypt

The Roman province of Egypt (Aegyptus) was established in 30 BC.
Egypt became a Roman province under the reign of Augustus in 30 BC, after his victory over Mark Anthony and Queen Cleopatra.
During the 1st and 2nd century, trading activity in the Roman province flourished.
The Roman province (Ancient Egypt Aegyptus) was a center for Christianity.
The Roman province supported principles like Arianism, Gnosticism, Manichaeism and Monasticism.
